I applaud the effort and twists and turns along the way, but I wasn't scared, laughing, or amused during this movie. I instead only thought of what could have been with a Fantasy Island movie.

Title: The Joker
Zach Comments: In the midst of all the rioting and violence going on outside my window as well as a myriad of places in this country, this movie speaks volumes about how the issues people face are two directional. A mentally unstable person hurts the world just as much as the world is hurting them forming a cyclical pattern. This happens in more than the movies. Bullying, homelessness, racism, sexism.. all these things force eternal chaos and hatred. Something needs to break that cycle. From what I know of the DC comics, Batman can't even break that evil so I'm not sure what the 'hero'-less world can do besides keep trying to show compassion.

Title: The Social Dilemma
Zach Comments: This movie is lucky it didn't receive a 1. It's hypocritical by nature using scare tactics and clear generalized targeting to manipulate people. It also blames tech companies for issues of a full technological society. Yes, tech companies are an issue and tech addiction is seriously hurting our society, but the fantasy scenes and dark ominous sound effects detract from the truth of the problem. Data should be regulated and companies should be responsible for false information, but there are non-profit and private companies who cause many of these issues at the same societal rate as these large social network companies.

Title: Cats
Zach Comments: To quote from Birth.Movies.Death: "The experience of seeing Cats is a singular one, so to speak. Tom Hooper's ill-advised adaptation of the most nonsensical musical of all time has been variously described as a disasterpiece, a thoroughly bizarre and deeply unsettling work of visual media, a piece of aggressive anti-art, a work of body horror that would make David Cronenberg cringe himself into oblivion, a confounding shitshow of digital tomfoolery, and then some. But humans are nothing if not morbidly curious and self-destructive, which would account for [why we watched this movie]"
